CHAPTER 6: STYLING IN REACT NATIVE:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Unlike web development, React Native does not use CSS files.

Instead, styles are written using JavaScript objects.

Example:

<Text style={{fontSize:20, color:'blue'}}>
 Hello
</Text>

React Native styling is based on Flexbox layout system, similar to CSS Flexbox.

6.1 Styling Basics:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::

There are three common ways to style components:

| Method                     | Usage         |
| -------------------------- | ------------- |
| Inline Styles              | quick styling |
| StyleSheet API             | recommended   |
| External styling libraries | advanced apps |


1️⃣ StyleSheet API (Recommended):-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

The StyleSheet API helps organize styles in a clean and reusable way.

Syntax:

StyleSheet.create({
  styleName: {}
})
Example
import React from 'react'
import {View, Text, StyleSheet} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  return(

    <View style={styles.container}>

      <Text style={styles.title}>
        React Native Styling
      </Text>

    </View>

  )
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({

  container:{
    flex:1,
    justifyContent:'center',
    alignItems:'center',
    backgroundColor:'lightblue'
  },

  title:{
    fontSize:24,
    fontWeight:'bold'
  }

})
Why StyleSheet is Better

Benefits:

✔ Better performance
✔ Code organization
✔ Reusable styles
✔ Easier maintenance

2️⃣ Inline Styles:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Inline styles are written directly inside components.

Example:

<Text style={{fontSize:20, color:'red'}}>
 Hello World
</Text>
Example
<View style={{
  backgroundColor:'yellow',
  padding:20
}}>
  <Text>Hello</Text>
</View>
When to Use Inline Styles

Inline styles are useful for:

quick styling

dynamic styles

small components

But large apps should prefer StyleSheet.

Common Styling Properties:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Some frequently used style properties:

| Property        | Purpose                 |
| --------------- | ----------------------- |
| backgroundColor | background color        |
| padding         | space inside component  |
| margin          | space outside component |
| borderRadius    | rounded corners         |
| fontSize        | text size               |
| color           | text color              |

Example:

<Text style={{
  fontSize:22,
  color:'blue',
  margin:10
}}>
Styled Text
</Text>

3️⃣ Flexbox Layout:-
::::::::::::::::::::::::::

React Native uses Flexbox for layout.

Flexbox helps arrange components:

Row
Column
Alignment
Spacing

Good news for you:
If you used Flutter Row/Column or Android layouts, Flexbox will feel familiar.

Default Layout Direction

In React Native:

flexDirection: column

So items are arranged vertically by default.

Example:

<View>
  <Text>Item 1</Text>
  <Text>Item 2</Text>
  <Text>Item 3</Text>
</View>

Output:

Item 1
Item 2
Item 3
flexDirection

Controls layout direction.
| Value  | Meaning    |
| ------ | ---------- |
| column | vertical   |
| row    | horizontal |

Example (Row Layout)
<View style={{flexDirection:'row'}}>

  <Text>One</Text>
  <Text>Two</Text>
  <Text>Three</Text>

</View>

Output:

One   Two   Three


justifyContent:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::

Controls alignment on the main axis.

| Value         | Meaning        |
| ------------- | -------------- |
| flex-start    | start          |
| center        | center         |
| flex-end      | end            |
| space-between | equal space    |
| space-around  | spacing around |


Example
<View style={{
  flexDirection:'row',
  justifyContent:'space-between'
}}>
alignItems

Controls alignment on the cross axis.

Example:

<View style={{
  alignItems:'center'
}}>

Centers items horizontally.

Example Layout:-
.....................
import React from 'react'
import {View, Text} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  return(

    <View style={{
      flex:1,
      flexDirection:'row',
      justifyContent:'space-around',
      alignItems:'center'
    }}>

      <Text>1</Text>
      <Text>2</Text>
      <Text>3</Text>

    </View>

  )
}

Flex Property:-
::::::::::::::::::::::

flex controls how much space a component occupies.

Example:

<View style={{flex:1}} />
<View style={{flex:2}} />

Second view gets twice the space.

Example Layout with Flex
<View style={{flex:1}}>

  <View style={{flex:1, backgroundColor:'red'}}/>

  <View style={{flex:2, backgroundColor:'blue'}}/>

</View>

Output:

Red section (small)
Blue section (larger)

justifyContent Values:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::
| Value         | Behavior                   |
| ------------- | -------------------------- |
| flex-start    | items start from beginning |
| center        | items centered             |
| flex-end      | items at end               |
| space-between | equal space between items  |
| space-around  | equal space around items   |
| space-evenly  | equal spacing everywhere   |

3️⃣ alignItems:-
::::::::::::::::::::::

alignItems controls alignment on the cross axis.

Cross axis is perpendicular to the main axis.

Example:

If:

flexDirection: row

then:

main axis = horizontal
cross axis = vertical
alignItems Values

| Value      | Behavior       |
| ---------- | -------------- |
| flex-start | align at start |
| center     | align center   |
| flex-end   | align at end   |
| stretch    | stretch items  |


6.3 Responsive Design:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Responsive design means:

UI adjusts automatically to different screen sizes and devices

For example:

Small phone → smaller layout
Large phone → wider layout
Tablet → multi-column layout

React Native provides APIs to help achieve this.

1️⃣ Dimensions API:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::

The Dimensions API provides the width and height of the device screen.

It helps us build layouts that adapt to screen size.

Import:

import {Dimensions} from 'react-native'
Getting Screen Size
const screen = Dimensions.get("window")

Example output:

{
  width: 360,
  height: 800,
  scale: 2,
  fontScale: 2
}
Example: Responsive Box
import React from 'react'
import {View, Dimensions, StyleSheet} from 'react-native'

const screenWidth = Dimensions.get("window").width

export default function App(){

  return(

    <View style={styles.container}>

      <View style={[styles.box, {width: screenWidth * 0.8}]} />

    </View>

  )
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({

container:{
flex:1,
justifyContent:'center',
alignItems:'center'
},

box:{
height:100,
backgroundColor:'blue'
}

})
Explanation
width: screenWidth * 0.8

This means:

80% of screen width

So on different phones:

Device	Width
Small phone	288px
Large phone	400px

The UI automatically adapts.

Listening to Screen Rotation:-
....................................

Phones may rotate.

Example:

Dimensions.addEventListener("change", ({window}) => {
  console.log(window.width, window.height)
})

Now the layout can update on orientation change.


2️⃣ Platform Module:-
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Sometimes Android and iOS need different styling or logic.

Example differences:

| Feature | Android            | iOS               |
| ------- | ------------------ | ----------------- |
| shadow  | elevation          | shadow properties |
| font    | Roboto             | San Francisco     |
| padding | slightly different |                   |

React Native provides the Platform module.

Import:

import {Platform} from 'react-native'
Detect Platform
Platform.OS

Output:

android

or

ios
Example
import React from 'react'
import {View, Text, Platform} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  return(

    <View>

      <Text>

        {Platform.OS === "android"
        ? "Running on Android"
        : "Running on iOS"}

      </Text>

    </View>

  )
}
Platform Specific Styling
const styles = {

button:{
padding: Platform.OS === "android" ? 10 : 20
}

}

Android button:

padding 10

iOS button:

padding 20
Platform.select()

Better method:

Platform.select({
  ios: {backgroundColor:'blue'},
  android: {backgroundColor:'green'}
})

Example:

const styles = StyleSheet.create({

container:{
flex:1,
backgroundColor: Platform.select({
ios:'lightblue',
android:'lightgreen'
})
}

})

3️⃣ PixelRatio:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::

Different phones have different pixel densities.

| Device      | Pixel Density |
| ----------- | ------------- |
| Low density | 1x            |
| Medium      | 2x            |
| High        | 3x            |


React Native provides PixelRatio API to handle this.

Import:

import {PixelRatio} from 'react-native'
Get Device Pixel Density
PixelRatio.get()

Example output:

3

Meaning:

3 device pixels = 1 layout pixel
Example: Adjust Font Size
import React from 'react'
import {Text, PixelRatio} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

const fontSize = 16 * PixelRatio.getFontScale()

return(

<Text style={{fontSize}}>
Responsive Text
</Text>

)

}

Now text adjusts based on device font scaling.

Example: Pixel Perfect Layout
PixelRatio.roundToNearestPixel(10.5)

Result:

11

This ensures sharp rendering on high density screens.

Real World Example

Responsive card layout:

import React from 'react'
import {View, Text, Dimensions} from 'react-native'

const width = Dimensions.get("window").width

export default function App(){

return(

<View style={{
width: width * 0.9,
height:150,
backgroundColor:'lightgray',
alignSelf:'center',
marginTop:50
}}>

<Text style={{fontSize:20}}>
Responsive Card
</Text>

</View>

)

}

The card always takes 90% of screen width.

Best Practices for Responsive Design

1️⃣ Use Flexbox instead of fixed sizes.

Example:

flex:1

2️⃣ Use percentage-based width.

Example:

width: Dimensions.get("window").width * 0.9

3️⃣ Avoid fixed pixel values.

Bad:

width: 400

Good:

width: "90%"

4️⃣ Test on different screen sizes.

Example:

small emulator

large emulator

tablet


6.4: Theming in React Native.:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
Theming is about maintaining a consistent design system across the entire app.

Modern mobile apps support:

Light mode ☀️

Dark mode 🌙

Global color themes

Reusable style systems

Examples of apps that support dark mode:

Instagram

WhatsApp

YouTube

In this section we will study:

1️⃣ Dark Mode
2️⃣ Global Styles
3️⃣ Styled Components

6.4 Theming:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Theming means creating a centralized design configuration.

Example:

Primary Color
Background Color
Text Color
Font Styles
Spacing

Instead of writing colors everywhere, we define them once and reuse them.

Example:

backgroundColor: theme.background
color: theme.text

1️⃣ Dark Mode:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Dark mode changes UI colors when the device is set to dark theme.

React Native provides the Appearance API to detect system theme.

Import:

import {Appearance} from 'react-native'
Detect Current Theme
const theme = Appearance.getColorScheme()

Output:

light

or

dark
Example: Dark Mode UI
import React from 'react'
import {View, Text, Appearance} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

const colorScheme = Appearance.getColorScheme()

const isDark = colorScheme === "dark"

return(

<View style={{
flex:1,
justifyContent:'center',
alignItems:'center',
backgroundColor: isDark ? "#000" : "#fff"
}}>

<Text style={{
color: isDark ? "#fff" : "#000"
}}>

Hello React Native

</Text>

</View>

)

}
Result

If device theme is:

Light mode:

White background
Black text

Dark mode:

Black background
White text
Auto Updating Theme

To respond when the user changes device theme:

Appearance.addChangeListener(({colorScheme}) => {
 console.log(colorScheme)
})

Now the UI updates automatically.


2️⃣ Global Styles:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Large apps use global styles to maintain consistent UI.

Instead of writing styles everywhere:

fontSize:20
color:"#333"

We create a central style file.

Example folder structure:

src
 ├── styles
 │    └── theme.js
Example Global Theme

theme.js

export const theme = {

colors:{
primary:"#3498db",
background:"#ffffff",
text:"#333333"
},

spacing:{
small:8,
medium:16,
large:24
}

}
Using Global Theme
import {theme} from './styles/theme'

<Text style={{
color: theme.colors.text
}}>
Hello
</Text>

Benefits:

✔ consistent design
✔ easier updates
✔ scalable apps

Example Global Styles File

globalStyles.js

import {StyleSheet} from 'react-native'

export const globalStyles = StyleSheet.create({

container:{
flex:1,
padding:16
},

title:{
fontSize:24,
fontWeight:'bold'
}

})
Usage
import {globalStyles} from './styles/globalStyles'

<View style={globalStyles.container}>
<Text style={globalStyles.title}>Hello</Text>
</View>



3️⃣ Styled Components:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Another popular styling method is Styled Components.

Library:

styled-components

It allows writing styles inside components using template syntax.

This approach is very popular in large React applications.

Install Styled Components
npm install styled-components
Example Styled Component
import styled from 'styled-components/native'

const Container = styled.View`
flex:1;
justify-content:center;
align-items:center;
background-color:lightblue;
`

const Title = styled.Text`
font-size:24px;
font-weight:bold;
`

export default function App(){

return(

<Container>
<Title>Hello Styled Components</Title>
</Container>

)

}
Benefits of Styled Components

✔ cleaner UI code
✔ dynamic styling
✔ reusable components
✔ better theming support

Styled Components + Theme

Example theme system:

const theme = {
colors:{
primary:"#6200ee",
background:"#ffffff"
}
}

Use:

<ThemeProvider theme={theme}>
<App/>
</ThemeProvider>

Then inside component:

background-color: ${props => props.theme.colors.primary};


Comparison:- 
...................


| Method            | Use Case                     |
| ----------------- | ---------------------------- |
| StyleSheet        | default React Native styling |
| Global Styles     | consistent app design        |
| Styled Components | component-based styling      |
